In article <310cs7$2jt@senator-bedfellow.MIT.EDU>, solman@athena.mit.edu (Jason W Solinsky) writes:
|> In article <30vrii$6p7@rzsun02.rrz.uni-hamburg.de>, bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev) writes:
|> 
|> |> Now, *this* I can easily agree with. Essentially, it says that
|> |> weakening the encryption by encrypting the same message twice with two
|> |> independently selected keys and strong cyphers is _highly unlikely_.
|> |> However, I understood your initial claim to mean that it is
|> |> _theoretically impossible_, which is what caused my comments. Sorry if
|> |> I have misunderstood you.
|> 
|> That's fine. I recently ran into a similar problem on cypherpunks when we were
|> discussing a paper by Chaum in which he demonstrates that it must be
|> computationally possible to identify transferable e-cash when you see it
|> twice, but not necessarilly computationally feasible. I find it amusing the
|> distinction that many cryptographic papers make between the possible and
|> the computationally possible given that the entire field of cryptography
|> (as it exists today) is dependent on computational infeasibility, not
|> impossibility.

Well, just to be pedantic, the One Time Pad _is_ impossible, done rightly.
So, I'm amused, too.  My memory is also falible. :-)

